## 1. Overview

## 1.1. Introduction

This datasheet provides a technical description of the Hailo-15H AI VPU (Vision Processor Unit) integrating both patented Hailo AI inferencing capabilities and advanced computer vision engines.

Hailo-15H empowers intelligence in IP cameras by enabling a broad range of AI applications based on integrated computer vision. Hailo-15H integrates an optimal mix of performance, low power and sophisticated video analytics processing.

This datasheet is applicable for HNC2HCI11SM and its derivative (HNC2HAI11SM).

logo

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

bar chart

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

VH

AIL

## 1.2. General Description

The Hailo-15™ are a series of AI vision processors for smart cameras.

The Hailo-15H System-on-a-Chip (SoC) combines Hailo's patented and field proven AI inferencing capabilities with advanced computer vision engines, generating premium image quality and advanced video analytics. The unprecedented AI capacity of up to 20 TOPS can be used for both AI-powered image enhancement and processing of multiple complex deep learning AI applications at full scale and at superior efficiency.

This is thanks to Hailo's market proven unique deep Neural Network (NN) Core processing, based on design elements, physically distributed computation and software abstraction. It contains NN Core, Application Processor, DSP subsystem, Vision subsystem with ISP pipeline and Video Encoder, a security subsystem and a variety of interfaces for image sensors, data, and memory.

## Unparalleled AI Analytics

- l Up to 20 TOPS (Tera Operations Per Second) on a powerful Neural Network (NN) Core enabling the processing of multiple advanced DL models in parallel.
- l High FPS deep learning model processing for faster and highly accurate detection of more objects per frame.
- l Best AI performance at a standard camera PC power consumption &amp; cost envelope.

## Superior Image Quality

- l AI-powered vision processing with low-light, image stabilization and image perfection capabilities, for enhanced image quality.
- l Premium 4k30 image quality with a cutting-edge ISP pipeline and an advanced Vision sub-system with High Dynamic Range (HDR) and Noise Reduction (NR) algorithms.
- l Industry leading DSP vision processing and high-quality video encoding.

## Flexible and Secure System

- l Industry-standard frameworks with a complete Yocto-based Linux distribution.
- l Industrial grade SoC with a variety of interfaces for image sensors, data, and memory.
- l Secure boot and secure debug with hardware accelerated crypto library, ARM ® TrustZone ® , TRNG, and Firewall.

## Comprehensive Software Suite

The vision processor software package includes a set of drivers, libraries and tools designed to develop smart cameras based on AI computer vision.

It includes all the support for camera hardware interfaces and protocols, as well as specialized image and video-processing algorithms and vision subsystem that are optimized for the requirements of camera-based applications.

## 1.3. Features

- l High-performance Hailo NN core subsystem
- o Hailo's patented structure defined dataflow architecture
- o NN core: 20 TOPs
- o Full software suite for continuous capabilities upgrades
- l AP sub-system
- o Quad-cores ARM ® Cortex ® A53@1.3 GHz 12 kDMIPS
- l DSP vision processing sub-system
- o Vector DSP
- o 256 MACs @ 700 MHz
- o Supports up to 350 GOPs
- l MCU sub-system
- l 2x Cortex M4 @ 200MHz
- l Vision sub-system
- o ISP: 12MP resolution, 600 Mpixel/s pixel rate
- o Supported cameras: 2
- o Video encoding: (HEVC &amp; AVC) H.265/H.264 4K30 + 720p30, 10/8 bit Multiple streams capability
- o Image stabilization, Lens Shading &amp; Distortion Correction, Digital Zoom, Flip &amp; Rotate
- o WDR for low light image processing
- o High Dynamic Range (HDR) support
- o Advanced noise reduction features: 2DNR, 3DNR, Chroma NR
- o Up to 3 exposures merging
- o RGGB &amp; RCCB CFAs support
- l Video

- , DVP 24-bit

- o Flash controller: SPI/DSPI/QSPI up to 4 devices
- o SDIO x2:SD ver6.0 4-bit SDR104 or eMMC 5.1 4-bit/8-bit (up to HS200)
- l Peripheral Interfaces

- o 10 / 100 / 1000 Ethernet with RMII / RGMII
- o USB3.1 Gen2 Host/Device, USB2.0 Host

- o UART (x4)

- l DMA
- o GP DMA 16 channels
- l Security
- o Secure boot, Secure debug
- o HWaccelerated crypto library
- o ARM ® TrustZone ® , TRNG, Firewall
- l Physical
- o Packaging: FCCSP 15x15 mm
- o Operating temperature -40 to 85 °C

## 2.3. Pin Multiplex Specifications

This section describes the possible multiplex configurations available for Hailo-15H GPIOs. Each of the 32 GPIOs has up to nine options.

Important: Each group of pins can only be set to the same option.

- l Option0 - pads\_pinmux\_mode[3:0] = [0000]
- l Option1 - pads\_pinmux\_mode[3:0] = [0001]
- l Option2 - pads\_pinmux\_mode[3:0] = [0010]
- l Option3 - pads\_pinmux\_mode[3:0] = [0011]
- l Option4 - pads\_pinmux\_mode[3:0] = [0100]
- l Option5 - pads\_pinmux\_mode[3:0] = [0101]
- l Option6 - pads\_pinmux\_mode[3:0] = [0110]
- l Option7 - pads\_pinmux\_mode[3:0] = [0111]
- l Option8 - pads\_pinmux\_mode[3:0] = [1000]
- l Option9 - pads\_pinmux\_mode[3:0] = [1001]

## 3.3. Power-up Sequence

The power-up sequence should follow these guidelines:

1. Initial state: NRESET pin is asserted (held low).
2. The VDDIO rises to 1.8V. Slew rate should be less than 18V/ms.
3. The VDD rises to 0.8V. VDD\_CORE must hold VDD\_CORE &lt;VDDIO-0.3V. Slew rate of VDD\_CORE should be less than 18V/ms.
4. DDR\_PLL\_VDDA and PLL\_VDDA should rise with VDD and be powered from VDD power regulator with filtering.
5. After VDD is stable:
- a. Power-up CSI\_RX\_AVDD and CSI\_RX\_AVDDH. Each power ramp-up should be between 100us and 2ms. CSI\_RX\_AVDDH and CSI\_RX\_AVDD can power-up in any order.
- b. Power-up DSI\_TX\_AVDD and DSI\_TX\_AVDDH. Each power ramp-up should be between 100us and 2ms. DSI\_TX\_AVDDH and DSI\_TX\_AVDD can power-up in any order.
- c. Power-up MPP\_AVDD\_D, MPP\_AVDD\_C, and MPP\_AVDD\_H in any order. There are no timing limitations (minimum or maximum) between powering-up multiple power supplies.
9. o MPP\_AVDD\_D, MPP\_AVDD\_C can be powered from VDD power regulator as long as noise target is met.
10. o MPP\_AVDD\_H can power prior to MPP\_AVDD\_D, MPP\_AVDD\_C
- d. Power-up DDR\_VDD, DDR\_VDDPLL, DDR\_VDDQX and DDR\_VDDQ.
12. o DDR\_VDD, DDR\_VDDPLL can short with VDD as long as VDD noise target is met. DDR\_VDD and DDR\_VDDPLL should be powered up earlier than DDR\_VDDQX and DDR\_VDDQ. DDR\_VDDQX must be rise at same time or earlier than DDR\_VDDQ, and DDR\_VDDQX must always be greater than or equal to DDR\_VDDQ.
- e. FUSE\_VQPS should rise later than VDD and power off before VDD is ramped down.
6. There is no particular voltage dependency for USB\_ AVDD\_CORE, VDD, USB\_AVDD\_IO and USB\_ AVDD\_IO\_HV supplies. USB\_AVDD\_CORE, USB\_AVDD\_IO, USB\_AVDD\_IO\_HV can be in any order, there is no specific ramp-up sequence between them and each supply ramp-up is independent of each other, Time of ramp up for all supply must be between 10μs to 5ms.
7. Between the supplied and VBUS - there is no specific ramp up, and VBUS can be present when there are either supplies or no supplies provided to the USB 2.0
8. Enable reference clock after VDDIO is stable.
9. De-assert NRESET after clock is stable.

Thermal models are performed to make a rough estimate during the initial stage of thermal design.

Thermal design shall take the above measurements into consideration with regards to the following thermal model:

T j = T a + P * Theta

T j : Junction temperature [°C]

T a : Ambient temperature [°C]

P: Average power consumption [W]

Theta: Thermal resistance [°C/W]

For example:

For a system design with an integrated H15 chip, that should support a T a of 45°C, and should execute a task similar to the 'Detection and Landmarks', then the thermal resistance should be designed according to:

( 105 [T j ] - 45 [T a ) / 7.15 [W with FF\0.8v\105°C] = Theta = 8.4 [°C/W]

## 3.4.3. Power Modes

## 3.4.3.1. Thermal Throttling

The thermal throttling mechanism's main purpose is to keep the Hailo-15 SOC from overheating during operation and exceeding absolute maximum ratings. The throttling mechanism is enabled by default but can be deactivated by the system integrator.

While it operates, the temperature sensors embedded in the chip silicon are configured to interrupt the SCU (ARM Cortex M4) executing Hailo FW when a temperature threshold is crossed.

When a temperature threshold cross is detected, Hailo FW starts to reduce the clock frequency of the NN-core and the AP (ARM Cortex A53), which should reduce the dynamic power of the chip and expectantly it's junction temperature.

The thermal throttling has three throttling levels, with three corresponding threshold values:

- l Light
- l Medium
- l Heavy

The higher the monitored temperature, the heavier the throttling level and therefore the clock frequency of the NN-core and AP will be further reduced.

In the case of an event indicating the monitored temperature is cooling down, the Hailo-15 FW will increase the NN-core and the AP clock frequency, and the temperature will pass a set of hysteresis thresholds, recovering the performance degradation.

## 4. Detailed Description

## whitSystem Modes and Usage Scenarios

This section describes various system modes and usage scenarios and provides detailed information on these various Hailo-15H subsystems.

See Hailo SW documentation for further descriptions.

## 4.1. Bootstraps

The Hailo-15H supports boot from flash memory, PCIe or from UART IF.

Hailo-15H has two bootstrap pins, which select the boot-up interface of the M4 MCU.

Note: Since the IF to which this pin is multiplexed to is not functional at this stage, the default pulldown resistor would pull this line down, therefore the signal level is determined by the internal pulldown and the external pull resistor (which is used to select the boot mode), until this signal will be driven from the SoC internals.

Table 60. Bootstrap pin names and functions

| Name and Function                                                                                          | Description                                                                                                                                   |   Default |
|------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|-----------|
| bs_io_sel[1:0] - bs_io_sel[0] multiplexed with i2s_sdo 1 uart0_tx - bs_io_sel[1] multiplexed with uart0_tx | IO select decoding bs_io_sel[1:0] = 00 - m4 MCU boot from serial (Q)SPI Flash (default) 01 - Boot from UART 10 - Boot from PCIe 11 - Reserved |        00 |

1 i2s\_sdo is the pin function after boot

## 4.2. Boot Modes

## 4.2.1. Boot from Flash

When this option is selected, ROM code reads the MCU image from an external (Q)SPI Flash device, authenticates it and executes the MCU code, which will in turn fetch the AP bootloader and release the AP reset to start its boot-up process.

Figure 12. Boot from Flash

flow chart

Diagram showing the boot from Flash flow, where ROM code reads the MCU image from an external (Q)SPI Flash device.

## 4.2.2. Boot from UART

This flow may be considered as a recovery flow, or as a production flow for initial Flash fusing. It is based on a simple proprietary data transfer protocol over the UART1 interface, which enables a device with empty flash to receive the MCU image over a UART interface, write the MCU FW to the flash, and then boot the device from the newly programmed flash.

Figure 13. Boot from UART

## 4.2.3. Boot from PCIe

For PCIe boot, the SoC ROM handles the process with the host platform that runs the Hailo RT PCIe driver. Firmware is then fetched over the PCIe link to boot the device firmware.

## 4.3. NN Core

The Hailo-15H NN Core enables efficient deployment of Deep NNs (DNNs) leveraging an architecture built around five internal functional units called clusters.

## Key features include:

- l Up to 20 TOPs with 8-bit precision and up to 40 TOPs with 4-bit precision.
- l Five clusters that can be used to deploy multiple NNs.
- o Scalable compute, control and memory structure optimized for NN primitives.
- o Fully programmable architecture to allow instantiation of all common NN building blocks, based on available software support delivered by the Hailo Dataflow Compiler (this includes, but is not limited to, layers such as convolution, pooling, fully connected and activation).
- o Support for advanced NN architecture with native support for split, concatenation and add layers.
- l Flexible I/O and interconnect. Up to 40 I/O channels to the NN core. Configurable interconnect between NN core inputs, outputs and pre/post units.
- l Precision configurability, support 4/8/16-bit precision for weights and activations, configurable at layer granularity.
- l Built-in support for weight and activation compression.
- l Multi-network pipelines supporting fast switching between multiple models, enabling efficient execution of sequential or parallel network pipelines with minimal overhead.
- l NN pre/post processing hardware accelerator used to offload the following functions from the host:
- o Up to 4 NMS engines
- o 4 Bi linear interpolation engines
- o 8 Reshape engines
- o 2 Softmax/normalization engines

## 4.4. High Bandwidth Interfaces

## 4.4.1. Ethernet

Not currently supported, if you wish to use this feature , please contact your Hailo support.

The Hailo-15H provides an IEEE-802.3-2002-compliant Media Access Controller (MAC) for Ethernet LAN communications through an industry-standard Reduced Gigabit Media-Independent Interface (RGMII) or Reduced Media-Independent Interface (RMII).  The Hailo-15H requires an external physical interface device (PHY) to connect to the physical LAN bus (twisted-pair, fiber, etc.). The MAC integrates a DMA, 1588 functionality, TSN/AVB and PCS for automotive applications.

Key features include:

bar chart

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

VH

AIL

- l 10/100/1000 Mbit/s rates
- l Dedicated DMA controller allowing high-speed transfers from the memory (DRMA) to peripherals or from the peripheral to memory.
- l Tagged MAC frame support (VLAN support)
- l TCP/IP and UDP offload
- l TCP segmentation and UDP fragmentation offload
- l Receive segment coalescing offload
- l MAC control sublayer (control frames)
- l 32-bit CRC generation and removal
- l Several address filtering modes for physical and multicast addresses (multicast and group addresses)
- l 32-bit status code for each transmitted or received frame
- l Internal FIFOs to buffer transmit and receive frames. Sizes of transmit and the receive FIFOs are 16KB and 4KB, respectively
- l Hardware Precision Time Protocol (PTP) in accordance with IEEE 1588 2008 (PTP V2) with the time stamp comparator connected to the TIM2 input
- l Time Stamping Unit (TSU) supports a 102-bit timer
- l Credit Based Shaping - TSN, 802.1Qav
- l Enhanced Scheduled Traffic - TSN, 802.1Qbv
- l Frame Replication and Elimination for Reliability - TSN, 802.1CB

## 4.4.2. PCI Express (PCIe)

Hailo-15H provides up to 4-lane PCI-SIG compliant PCIe® gen 3 PHY and controller, Endpoint or RC, enabling it to be integrated as a PCIe root complex. It also integrates a dedicated scatter-gather DMA for efficient memory mapped transactions.

PCIe requires a 100MHz clock oscillator on board for its reference clock.

## Key features include:

- l Up to 32 Gbps bi-directional throughput
- o X1/X2/X4 lanes
- o Shares one PHY with USB 3.x, therefore when USB is used, PCIe can use up X1/X2 lanes only.
- o Supports link rate of 2.5, 5.0, 8.0 GT/s per lane
- l Lane reversal support
- l L1 PM Sub-states with CLKREQ
- l Latency Tolerance Reporting (LTR)
- l Multiple endpoints support (through PCIe switch)
- l Up to 2.5μs read latency from host memory in full BW

bar chart

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

VH

AIL

- l Supports also Device low power modes  - D0, D3
- l Up to 4K Byte maximum payload size
- l Advanced Error Reporting (AER) support
- l ECRC generation and check support
- l MSI (up to 32 per device ID) support
- l Internal DMA (32 channels) for host direct access to EP
- l Retransmit and receive buffer of 2KB
- l Up to 32 outstanding read requests
- l Integrated safety mechanisms that detect transient and permanent faults in data and control paths
- l Full support for link power management including ASPM L0, ASPM L1, L1.1, L1.2 and L2
- l Enhanced configuration access mechanism (ECAM) of 256MB support
- l Up to 16 address translation tables (ATR) for indirect memory space access

## 4.4.3. MIPI CSI-2

Hailo15H integrates two MIPI ® CSI-2 ® v1.3 RX controllers coupled to two MIPI RX D-PHY TM v1.2 with four lanes per D-PHY (2.5Gbps per lane), as well as DSI controller coupled to four data lanes and one clock lane TX D-PHY v1.2 (2.5Gbps per lane). This allows easy interfacing to sensors at the input side and displays at the output side.

## 4.4.3.1. CSI-RX

The CSI-2-RX subsystem allows efficient streaming of pixel data to the Hailo-15H NN core. The CSI-2-RX is responsible for handling a MIPI CSI-2 protocol-based camera sensor or sensor data stream, and for unpacking the payload data and forwarding it to the pixel stream interfaces. The CSI-2-RX allows the selection of multiple independent input streams and supports the control of the destination for each stream (ISP or NN core) along with the RFU. See Figure 15.

Key features include:

## Operation modes:

- l High-Speed (HS): maximum up to 2.5Gbps per lane
- l Escape mode
- o Remote triggers
- o LP-DT: up to 10Mbps
- o ULPS mode

Supports up to four streams for each interface over distinct virtual channels and for different data types.

Supports the following data types:

bar chart

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

VH

AIL

- l RAW6, RAW7, RAW8, RAW10, RAW12, RAW14, RAW16
- l RGB444, RGB555, RGB565, RGB666, RGB888
- l YUV420 10-bit, YUV 420 8-bit, YUV422 10-bit, YUV 422 8-bit,
- l User Defined/Embedded Data 8-bit and 16-bit

## 4.4.3.2. DSI-TX

The DSI-TX subsystem is intended to allow easy integration with external displays. The integrated DSI controller is coupled with TX -DPHY (4 lanes, 2.5 Gbps per lane), to allow scan out of frame buffers from SoCs DRAM.

## 4.4.4. Camera Parallel LVCMOS Interface

Hailo-15H integrates a camera parallel LVCMOS interface port of up to 24 bits wide at up to 66MHz, that connects to the video data bus from an image sensor.

## 4.4.5. Universal Serial Bus Interface

Hailo-15H contains an embedded USB 3.1 gen2 USB controller and PHY with a single port. It is also backward compliant with the USB 2.0 specification.

## Key features include:

- l USB3.1 supports host\device modes. USB2.0 supports host mode.
- l Compliant with USB 3.1 and xHCI 1.1 specifications.
- l Supports SS, SS+, HS, FS and LS protocols
- l Supports link power modes for USB2 (L1/L2) and USB3 (U1/U2/U3)
- l In host mode:
- o Supports up to 64 slots
- o Up to 128 periodic endpoints
- o 256 primary streams supported
- o MSI support
- l In device mode:
- o Control transfers by EP#0
- o Up to 7 IN + 7 OUT programmable endpoints
- l Support also Device low power modes - D0, D3
- l Internal DMA for efficient memory access

## 4.4.7. Network on Chip (NoC)

Hailo-15H integrates two Cortex M4 cores with a memory subsystem.

## 4.6.1. Cortex M4 Cores

Each of the two Cortex M4 MCU cores is equipped with a Memory Protection Unit (MPU) and a Floating Point Accelerator Unit (FPU) engine.

The cores communicate with each other through mailbox and semaphore modules.

Key features include:

The MCU memory is accessible through both cores.

Hailo-15H can access external Flash devices either directly through the QSPI controller or through the Flash caching system. The Flash caching system can cache read only instruction memory up to 512B.

- l Configurable fetching
- l Configurable ECC on the cached data

RFU (Routing and Filtering Unit) is for routing data from the MIPI IFs to the SoC internal modules according to VC and DT.

ISP is mainly for the processing of data coming from imaging sensors.

## 4.13. System Peripherals

## 4.13.1. Temperature Sensor

The Hailo-15H temperature sensor is a high-precision low-power junction temperature sensor embedded in the chip. Typical temperature sensor applications may include clock speed optimization, power management and thermal management.

## Key features include:

- l +/- 3.0°C accuracy
- l 12-bit resolution (10-bit and 8-bit alternatives at lower accuracy), parallel or serial
- l Signature response on demand
- l Analog fault coverage

## 4.13.2. Voltage Monitor

Hailo-15H embeds two on-chip voltage monitors that are low-power self-contained blocks designed to monitor differential voltage levels within the core logic voltage domains.

## Key features include:

- l 16 monitoring points
- l +/-1% accuracy
- l Up to 14-bit resolution
- l Digital interface
- l Signature response on demand
- l Analog fault coverage

## 4.13.3. DMA

The Hailo-15H integrates a DMA module, to easily move and copy data around the SoC.

Key features include:

- l Each DMA has 8 configurable channels.
- l Transfer of Peripheral to Memory, Memory to Peripheral, Memory to Memory and Peripheral to Peripheral.
- l Supports hardware handshake interfaces for I2C and UART modules

## 4.13.4. General-Purpose Input Output (GPIO)

Hailo-15H integrates up to 32 GPIOs. Each of the GPIO pins can be configured by software as output (push-pull or open-drain, with or without pull-up or pull-down), as input (floating, with or without pullup or pull-down) or as a peripheral alternate function. Most of the GPIO pins are shared with digital alternate functions. All GPIOs are high-current-capable and have speed selection to better manage internal noise, power consumption and electromagnetic emission.

The I/O alternate function configuration can be locked if needed by following a specific sequence to avoid spurious writing to the I/O registers.

Hailo-15H integrates four timers that can be programmed through the GPIO interfaces.

Key features include:

- l 32-bit counter
- l Clock from external clock input or internal clock
- l Interrupt output to MCU system

All timer counters can be frozen in debug mode.

## 4.13.6. Watchdog

The Hailo-15H integrates 2 watchdogs as a safety module to monitor the CPUs in the system.

Key features include:

- l 32-bit counter.
- l Configurable Interrupt threshold
- l Configurable system reset threshold

## 4.13.7. Mailbox

Hailo-15H integrates ARM PL-320 mailbox IP, used to transfer information between MCU cores, application processor and DSP.

The mailbox includes internal 16 different mailboxes that can be used in parallel. Each internal mailbox corresponds to a dedicated request and acknowledge interrupt. It also encapsulates a corresponding message data register.

Mailbox can be used to perform both unicast and multicast messages.

## 4.13.8. Semaphore

Hailo-15H integrates eight semaphore units to control MCUs access to a common resource.

## 4.13.9. CRC Hardware Offload Engine

Hailo-15H includes an internal CRC generator and calculator to accelerate CRC calculation on data and control.

Key features include:

- l Generate and check CRC
- l CRC32/CRC16 polynomials
- l CRC calculation on 32/16-bit data width

The Hailo-15H integrates a PWM controller to support up to 6 pulse-width modulators for multiple applications such as motor control.

## 4.14. Security System

## 4.14.1. Features

Hailo-15H implements a wide range of security features for typical target applications.

The security subsystem includes:

- l Secure boot
- l Complete Life Cycle Management (LCM)
- l User access to hardware-accelerated cryptographic algorithms
- l Secure debug access according to the product life cycle
- l Inner configurable firewall to block unexpected access to secure system regions

## 4.14.2. Lifecycle Management

Hailo-15H has lifecycle support for Hailo's production and integrator development processes, as well as for product deployment and Return Merchandise Authorization (RMA).

The debug interface lock depends on the lifecycle state.

## 4.14.3. True Random Number Generator (TRNG)

Hailo-15H contains a TRNG that delivers 32-bit random numbers produced by an integrated analog circuit.

The TRNG is fully compliant with FIPS 140-2.

## 4.14.4. Cryptographic Accelerator

Hailo-15H contains a hardware authentication engine and an encryption/decryption engine that support the following algorithms:

- l AES (128,192,256)
- l SHA1/2
- l RSA (2048,3072,4096)

The cryptographic accelerator can be used for secure boot, data-at-rest and data-in-transit.

## 4.14.5. Trusted Execution Environment (TEE)

The Hailo-15H TEE monitors and controls incoming and outgoing traffic inside the chip based on predetermined security rules set during software boot.

The Hailo-15H security system has a configurable hardware firewall. It protects access to peripherals inside the chip, internal SRAMs and external memory regions.
